TY  - JOUR
T1  - Understanding the Role of Worker Interdependence in Team Selection
AU  - Millhiser, William P.
AU  - Coen, Corinne A.
AU  - Solow, Daniel
Y1  - 2010/07/28
PY  - 2010
DA  - 2011/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.1100.0549
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.1100.0549
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 772
EP  - 787
VL  - 22
IS  - 3
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In this paper, we evaluate the effectiveness of policies for assigning interdependent workers to teams. Using a computational simulation, we contrast distributing workers equitably across teams based on prior individual performance with policies that distribute workers based on how well people work together. First, we test a policy that clusters workers into teams by finding natural breakpoints among them where their mutual support is weak. Then we test two other policies that both protect the strongest interdependent core of high performers but differ in that one policy separates workers who give little support to interdependent partners and the other separates workers who receive little support from their partners. All three policies outperform the equitable-distribution approach in some circumstances. We make recommendations to managers for harnessing interdependence when forming teams, whether the managers are familiar or unfamiliar with how well their people work together.
AB  - In this paper, we evaluate the effectiveness of policies for assigning interdependent workers to teams. Using a computational simulation, we contrast distributing workers equitably across teams based on prior individual performance with policies that distribute workers based on how well people work together. First, we test a policy that clusters workers into teams by finding natural breakpoints among them where their mutual support is weak. Then we test two other policies that both protect the strongest interdependent core of high performers but differ in that one policy separates workers who give little support to interdependent partners and the other separates workers who receive little support from their partners. All three policies outperform the equitable-distribution approach in some circumstances. We make recommendations to managers for harnessing interdependence when forming teams, whether the managers are familiar or unfamiliar with how well their people work together.
